      "body" : "I don't think this will work in the case of `filter` being unused. I'm getting the following compilation error: \r\n```\r\nIn file included from merkleblock.cpp:6:0:\r\n\r\nmerkleblock.h: In constructor Ã¢ÂÂCMerkleBlock::CMerkleBlock(const CBlock&, const std::set<uint256>&)Ã¢ÂÂ:\r\nmerkleblock.h:145:93: error: invalid initialization of non-const reference of type Ã¢ÂÂCBloomFilter&Ã¢ÂÂ from an rvalue of type Ã¢ÂÂCBloomFilterÃ¢ÂÂ\r\n     CMerkleBlock(const CBlock& block, const std::set<uint256>& txids) : CMerkleBlock(block, CBloomFilter(), txids) {}\r\n                                                                                             ^~~~~~~~~~~~~~\r\nmerkleblock.h:148:5: note:   initializing argument 2 of Ã¢ÂÂCMerkleBlock::CMerkleBlock(const CBlock&, CBloomFilter&, const std::set<uint256>&)Ã¢ÂÂ\r\n     CMerkleBlock(const CBlock& block, CBloomFilter& filter, const std::set<uint256>& txids);\r\n     ^~~~~~~~~~~~\r\n```\r\n\r\nApparently we can't create an unnamed, non-const `CBloomFilter` reference from an rvalue. I'm not sure how to avoid this when using constructor delegation.",
